{"title_page": "Sounwave", "text_new": "{{short description|American record producer and songwriter}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=Broken references; poor sourcing; adhere to MOS|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Sounwave\n| image           = Sounwave.jpg\n| caption         = \n| background      = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name      = Mark Anthony Spears\n| birth_place     = [[Compton, California]], U.S.\n| origin          = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n*Record producer\n*songwriter\n}}\n| years_active    = 2005\u2013present\n| label           = [[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]]\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* [[FL Studio]]\n* [[MPC2000]]\n* [[Akai MPC]]\n* Acid Pro 3.0\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Black Hippy]]\n* [[Skhye Hutch]]\n* [[Digi+Phonics]]\n* [[Red Hearse]]\n}}\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Mark Anthony Spears''', known professionally as '''Sounwave''', is an American hip-hop record producer and songwriter from [[Compton, California]],<ref name=\"xxlmag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/2013/05/istandard-producers-weigh-in-on-xxls-2013-freshman-producers-list/14/ |title=iStandard Producers Weigh In On XXL's 2013 Freshman Producers List - Page 14 of 16 - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-05-01 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> and an original member of the Californian hip-hop label, [[Top Dawg Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-sounwave-black-panther-kendrick-lamar-grammys-oscars-20190131-story.html|title=Kendrick Lamar's secret weapon? His right-hand man, 'Black Panther' soundtrack producer Sounwave|author=Mikael Wood|newspaper=[[The LA Times]]|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019|quote=}}</ref> Sounwave has worked on every [[Kendrick Lamar]] studio album since the 2009 [[Kendrick Lamar (EP)|Lamar's self-titled EP]], including the [[Grammy Award]]-winning albums ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'', ''[[To Pimp a Butterfly]]'', and the multi-Grammy and [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning album ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]''. He has received two Grammy Awards: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] (2015) for \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\", and [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]] (2017) for ''Damn''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sounwave-how-the-kendrick-lamar-and-black-panther-producer-quietly-made-americas-soundtrack-629632/| title=Sounwave: How the Kendrick Lamar and 'Black Panther' Producer Quietly Made America's Soundtrack | author=Jeff Weiss | date=28 May 2019 | accessdate=12 December 2019 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|quote=If he desired, Sounwave could easily reap millions farming his beats out to the corniest names in popular music. Instead, he's so self-effacing and averse to self-promotion that doesn't even have his own Wikipedia page.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gq.com/story/sounwave-kendrick-lamar-damn|title=Why Kendrick Lamar and Sounwave Camped Out in Sleeping Bags to Make DAMN.|magazine=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|author=Dan Hyman|date=22 April 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019|quote=The Grammy-winning producer and longtime Kendrick whisperer Mark \"Sounwave\" Spears takes us behind the scenes.\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nHailing from Compton, Sounwave credits \"[[Up Jumps da Boogie]]\" by [[Timbaland]] as the first hip hop instrumental he ever listened to. From the age of ten he started using a [[Korg]] drum machine to make simple drum beats. From there, he graduated to a 4-track machine and then to the MTV Music Generator for [[PlayStation]]. After using that for a while, he hooked up with rapper [[Bishop Lamont]] from [[Carson, California]], and a song he produced for him with MTV Music Generator received local radio placement.<ref name=\"thefader1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/12/04/beat-construction-sounwave/ |title=Beat Construction: Sounwave \u00ab The FADER |publisher=Thefader.com |date=2012-12-04 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===2005\u20132008===\n\nIn 2005, Sounwave was originally discovered by Top Dawg Entertainment co-founder [[Punch (rapper)|Terrence \"Punch\" Henderson]], who had him meet with TDE CEO, Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith. Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith was originally unimpressed with Sounwave, however, he persisted and honed his craft which ended up \"blowing away\" Tiffith.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/let-the-beat-build/let-the-beat-build-digi-phonics-on-kendrick-lamar-and-dr-dre |title=Let The Beat Build - Digi-Phonics On Kendrick Lamar & Dr. Dre &#124; Let The Beat Build &#124; Noisey |publisher=Noisey.vice.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> It was then he became a member of [[Digi+Phonics]], an American [[hip hop production]] team, composed of fellow [[California]]-based [[record producer]]s Tae Beast, Dave Free and Willie B. They served as the main in-house producers for [[Carson, California|Carson]]-based [[record label]], [[Top Dawg Entertainment]]. [[Digi+Phonics]] worked significantly on projects from all the members of hip hop [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[Black Hippy]], who are also signed to Top Dawg and is composed of rappers [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Jay Rock]], [[Schoolboy Q]], and [[Ab-Soul]].\n\n===2009\u20132016===\n\nSounwave's earliest work for [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] surfaced on the self-titled ''[[Kendrick Lamar (EP)|Kendrick Lamar]]'', and [[Jay Rock]]'s compilation track \"Fa Sho\" in 2009 and 2010 respectively.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |last=Sutherland |first=Sam |url=http://www.aux.tv/2013/03/heat-rising-sounwave-made-his-first-beats-using-a-video-game-and-now-hes-top-dawg-entertainment-family/ |title=HEAT RISING: Sounwave made his first beats using a video game, and now he's Top Dawg Entertainment family |publisher=Aux.tv |date=2013-03-20 |accessdate=2013-09-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111033839/http://www.aux.tv/2013/03/heat-rising-sounwave-made-his-first-beats-using-a-video-game-and-now-hes-top-dawg-entertainment-family/ |archive-date=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2011, Sounwave produced the bulk of Lamar's mixtape/album ''[[Section.80]]'', which landed him on ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''{{'}}s \"15 New Producers to Watch\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/07/15-new-producers-to-watch-out-for/sounwave |title=Sounwave \u2014 15 New Producers To Watch Out For |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> He also produced three songs on Lamar's critically acclaimed second album ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> Sounwave is best known for producing Kendrick Lamar's hit single \"[[Bitch Don't Kill My Vibe]]\", among other songs such as \"[[M.A.A.D. City]]\", \"[[A.D.H.D (Kendrick Lamar song)|A.D.H.D]]\" and [[Schoolboy Q]]'s \"There He Go\".<ref name=\"complex1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/10/25-new-producers-to-watch-out-for/digi-phonics |title=Digi + Phonics \u2014 25 New Producers To Watch Out For |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref><ref name=\"xxlmag1\"/> In 2014, he earned a placement on Top Dawg Entertainment artist [[Isaiah Rashad]]'s ''[[Cilvia Demo]]'' and produced \"Hoover Street\" and \"Prescription/Oxymoron\" on Schoolboy Q's ''Oxymoron''. Outside of his work with artists in the Top Dawg Entertainment label, he worked with [[Flo Rida]] on the song \"Finally Here\" from the latter's second album ''[[R.O.O.T.S.]]'' (2009).<ref name=\"thefader1\"/> Sounwave is also credited with production on four tracks on Schoolboy Q's fourth studio album, ''[[Blank Face LP]]''.\n\n===2016\u2013present===\n\nIn 2016, Sounwave worked alongside Lamar and Top Dawg Entertainment's CEO Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith as co-writer, A&R, and producer of ''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther: The Album]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/meet-sounwave-kendrick-lamar-and-black-panther-producer-w520584|title=Sounwave: How the Kendrick Lamar and 'Black Panther' Producer Quietly Made America's Soundtrack|first=Jeff|last=Weiss|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 29, 2018|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> the official soundtrack to the film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''. His work on the film's single \"[[All the Stars]]\" with Lamar and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] earned nominations for Best Original Song for the [[Academy Awards]], [[Golden Globe Awards]], and [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]].\n\nOutside of Top Dawg Entertainment, Sounwave has collaborated with [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Mary J Blige]], and many others. In 2019, Sounwave co-wrote and co-produced the song \"London Boy\" for [[Taylor Swift]]'s seventh studio album ''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'' (2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/taylor-swift-lover-full-album-credits|title=Here are the full credits for Taylor Swift's new album, Lover|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\n==Songwriting and production discography==\n\n===Songs===\n====2011====\n\n* \"[[A.D.H.D (Kendrick Lamar song)|A.D.H.D]]\" \u2013 [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n* \"[[Hol' Up (Kendrick Lamar song)|Hol' Up]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[No Make-Up (Her Vice)]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[The Spiteful Chant]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Schoolboy Q]]\n\n====2012====\n\n* \"[[M.A.A.D City|m.A.A.d city]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2013====\n\n* \"[[Bitch, Don't Kill My Vibe]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2014====\n\n* \"[[Break the Bank (song)|Break the Bank]]\" \u2013 Schoolboy Q\n\n====2015====\n\n* \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2016====\n\n* \"[[That Part]]\" \u2013 Schoolboy Q, [[Kanye West]]\n* \u201c[[Blank Face LP|John Muir]]\u201d \u2014 Schoolboy Q\n\n====2017====\n\n* \"[[Element (song)|Element]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Feel (Kendrick Lamar song)|Feel]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[God (Kendrick Lamar song)|God]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Love (Kendrick Lamar song)|Love]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Zacari]]\n* \"[[Loyalty (Kendrick Lamar song)|Loyalty]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Rihanna]]\n* \"[[Lust (Kendrick Lamar song)|Lust]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[XXX (Kendrick Lamar song)|XXX]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Yah (song)|Yah]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2018====\n\n* \"[[All the Stars]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[SZA (singer)|SZA]]\n* \"[[Big Shot (Kendrick Lamar song)|Big Shot]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Travis Scott]]\n* \"[[Black Panther (Kendrick Lamar song)|Black Panther]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Bloody Waters (song)|Bloody Waters]]\" \u2013 [[Ab-Soul]], [[Anderson .Paak]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]\n* \"[[I Am (Jorja Smith song)|I Am]]\" \u2013 [[Jorja Smith]], Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[King's Dead]]\" \u2013 [[Jay Rock]], Kendrick Lamar, [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]\n* \"[[Opps (song)|Opps]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[Vince Staples]], Yugen Blakrok\n* \"[[Paramedic!]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[SOB x RBE]], [[Zacari]]\n* \"[[Seasons (Mozzy song)|Seasons]]\" \u2013 [[Mozzy]], [[Sjava]], [[Reason]]\n* \"[[The Ways (song)|The Ways]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[Khalid]], [[Swae Lee]]\n* \"[[X (Schoolboy Q, 2 Chainz and Saudi song)|X]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, Schoolboy Q, [[2 Chainz]], [[Saudi (musician)|Saudi]]\n\n====2019====\n\n*\"[[The Lion King: The Gift|Nile]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n*\"[[Lover (album)|London Boy]]\" \u2013 [[Taylor Swift]]\n\n===Albums===\n\n*''[[Section.80]]'' \u2013 Kendrick Lamar (2011)\n*''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther]]'' \u2013 Kendrick Lamar (2018)\n*''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'' \u2013 [[Taylor Swift]] (2019)\n*''[[The Lion King: The Gift]]'' - [[Beyonc\u00e9]] (2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===[[Academy Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Pictures (Original Song) \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Golden Globe Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Pictures (Original Song) \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]]===\n* Won: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] \u2013 \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'' (2013)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[To Pimp a Butterfly]]'' (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]'' (2017)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther]]'' (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] \u2013 \"[[King's Dead]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for Visual Media]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Guild of Music Supervisors Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Pictures (Original Song) \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=nm6263328}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sounwave (Mark Anthony Spears)}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners for rap music]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Compton, California]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Music winners]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Top Dawg Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American record producer and songwriter}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=Broken references; poor sourcing; adhere to MOS|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Sounwave\n| image           = Sounwave.jpg\n| caption         = \n| background      = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name      = Mark Anthony Spears\n| birth_place     = [[Compton, California]], U.S.\n| origin          = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n*Record producer\n*songwriter\n}}\n| years_active    = 2005\u2013present\n| label           = [[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]]\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* [[FL Studio]]\n* [[MPC2000]]\n* [[Akai MPC]]\n* Acid Pro 3.0\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Black Hippy]]\n* [[Skhye Hutch]]\n* [[Digi+Phonics]]\n* [[Red Hearse]]\n}}\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Mark Anthony Spears''', known professionally as '''Sounwave''', is an American hip-hop record producer and songwriter from [[Compton, California]],<ref name=\"xxlmag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/2013/05/istandard-producers-weigh-in-on-xxls-2013-freshman-producers-list/14/ |title=iStandard Producers Weigh In On XXL's 2013 Freshman Producers List - Page 14 of 16 - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-05-01 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> and an original member of the Californian hip-hop label, [[Top Dawg Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-sounwave-black-panther-kendrick-lamar-grammys-oscars-20190131-story.html|title=Kendrick Lamar's secret weapon? His right-hand man, 'Black Panther' soundtrack producer Sounwave|author=Mikael Wood|newspaper=[[The LA Times]]|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019|quote=}}</ref> Sounwave has worked on every [[Kendrick Lamar]] studio album since the 2009 [[Kendrick Lamar (EP)|Lamar's self-titled EP]], including the [[Grammy Award]]-winning albums ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'', ''[[To Pimp a Butterfly]]'', and the multi-Grammy and [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning album ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]''. He has received two Grammy Awards: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] (2015) for \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\", and [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]] (2017) for ''Damn''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sounwave-how-the-kendrick-lamar-and-black-panther-producer-quietly-made-americas-soundtrack-629632/| title=Sounwave: How the Kendrick Lamar and 'Black Panther' Producer Quietly Made America's Soundtrack | author=Jeff Weiss | date=28 May 2019 | accessdate=12 December 2019 | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|quote=If he desired, Sounwave could easily reap millions farming his beats out to the corniest names in popular music. Instead, he's so self-effacing and averse to self-promotion that doesn't even have his own Wikipedia page.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gq.com/story/sounwave-kendrick-lamar-damn|title=Why Kendrick Lamar and Sounwave Camped Out in Sleeping Bags to Make DAMN.|magazine=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|author=Dan Hyman|date=22 April 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019|quote=The Grammy-winning producer and longtime Kendrick whisperer Mark \"Sounwave\" Spears takes us behind the scenes.\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nHailing from Compton, Sounwave credits \"[[Up Jumps da Boogie]]\" by [[Timbaland]] as the first hip hop instrumental he ever listened to. From the age of ten he started using a [[Korg]] drum machine to make simple drum beats. From there, he graduated to a 4-track machine and then to the MTV Music Generator for [[PlayStation]]. After using that for a while, he hooked up with rapper [[Bishop Lamont]] from [[Carson, California]], and a song he produced for him with MTV Music Generator received local radio placement.<ref name=\"thefader1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/12/04/beat-construction-sounwave/ |title=Beat Construction: Sounwave \u00ab The FADER |publisher=Thefader.com |date=2012-12-04 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===2005\u20132008===\n\nIn 2005, Sounwave was originally discovered by Top Dawg Entertainment co-founder [[Punch (rapper)|Terrence \"Punch\" Henderson]], who had him meet with TDE CEO, Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith. Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith was originally unimpressed with Sounwave, however, he persisted and honed his craft which ended up \"blowing away\" Tiffith.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/let-the-beat-build/let-the-beat-build-digi-phonics-on-kendrick-lamar-and-dr-dre |title=Let The Beat Build - Digi-Phonics On Kendrick Lamar & Dr. Dre &#124; Let The Beat Build &#124; Noisey |publisher=Noisey.vice.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> It was then he became a member of [[Digi+Phonics]], an American [[hip hop production]] team, composed of fellow [[California]]-based [[record producer]]s Tae Beast, Dave Free and Willie B. They served as the main in-house producers for [[Carson, California|Carson]]-based [[record label]], [[Top Dawg Entertainment]]. [[Digi+Phonics]] worked significantly on projects from all the members of hip hop [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[Black Hippy]], who are also signed to Top Dawg and is composed of rappers [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Jay Rock]], [[Schoolboy Q]], and [[Ab-Soul]].\n\n===2009\u20132016===\n\nSounwave's earliest work for [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] surfaced on the self-titled ''[[Kendrick Lamar (EP)|Kendrick Lamar]]'', and [[Jay Rock]]'s compilation track \"Fa Sho\" in 2009 and 2010 respectively.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |last=Sutherland |first=Sam |url=http://www.aux.tv/2013/03/heat-rising-sounwave-made-his-first-beats-using-a-video-game-and-now-hes-top-dawg-entertainment-family/ |title=HEAT RISING: Sounwave made his first beats using a video game, and now he's Top Dawg Entertainment family |publisher=Aux.tv |date=2013-03-20 |accessdate=2013-09-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111033839/http://www.aux.tv/2013/03/heat-rising-sounwave-made-his-first-beats-using-a-video-game-and-now-hes-top-dawg-entertainment-family/ |archive-date=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2011, Sounwave produced the bulk of Lamar's mixtape/album ''[[Section.80]]'', which landed him on ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''{{'}}s \"15 New Producers to Watch\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/07/15-new-producers-to-watch-out-for/sounwave |title=Sounwave \u2014 15 New Producers To Watch Out For |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> He also produced three songs on Lamar's critically acclaimed second album ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> Sounwave is best known for producing Kendrick Lamar's hit single \"[[Bitch Don't Kill My Vibe]]\", among other songs such as \"[[M.A.A.D. City]]\", \"[[A.D.H.D (Kendrick Lamar song)|A.D.H.D]]\" and [[Schoolboy Q]]'s \"There He Go\".<ref name=\"complex1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/10/25-new-producers-to-watch-out-for/digi-phonics |title=Digi + Phonics \u2014 25 New Producers To Watch Out For |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref><ref name=\"xxlmag1\"/> In 2014, he earned a placement on Top Dawg Entertainment artist [[Isaiah Rashad]]'s ''[[Cilvia Demo]]'' and produced \"Hoover Street\" and \"Prescription/Oxymoron\" on Schoolboy Q's ''Oxymoron''. Outside of his work with artists in the Top Dawg Entertainment label, he worked with [[Flo Rida]] on the song \"Finally Here\" from the latter's second album ''[[R.O.O.T.S.]]'' (2009).<ref name=\"thefader1\"/> Sounwave is also credited with production on four tracks on Schoolboy Q's fourth studio album, ''[[Blank Face LP]]''.\n\n===2016\u2013present===\n\nIn 2016, Sounwave worked alongside Lamar and Top Dawg Entertainment's CEO Anthony \"Top Dawg\" Tiffith as co-writer, A&R, and producer of ''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther: The Album]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/meet-sounwave-kendrick-lamar-and-black-panther-producer-w520584|title=Sounwave: How the Kendrick Lamar and 'Black Panther' Producer Quietly Made America's Soundtrack|first=Jeff|last=Weiss|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 29, 2018|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> the official soundtrack to the film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''. His work on the film's single \"[[All the Stars]]\" with Lamar and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] earned nominations for Best Original Song for the [[Academy Awards]], [[Golden Globe Awards]], and [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]].\n\nOutside of Top Dawg Entertainment, Sounwave has collaborated with [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Mary J Blige]], and many others. In 2019, Sounwave co-wrote and co-produced the song \"London Boy\" for [[Taylor Swift]]'s seventh studio album ''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'' (2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/taylor-swift-lover-full-album-credits|title=Here are the full credits for Taylor Swift's new album, Lover|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\n==Songwriting and production discography==\n\n===Songs===\n====2011====\n\n* \"[[A.D.H.D (Kendrick Lamar song)|A.D.H.D]]\" \u2013 [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n* \"[[Hol' Up (Kendrick Lamar song)|Hol' Up]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[No Make-Up (Her Vice)]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[The Spiteful Chant]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Schoolboy Q]]\n\n====2012====\n\n* \"[[M.A.A.D City|m.A.A.d city]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2013====\n\n* \"[[Bitch, Don't Kill My Vibe]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2014====\n\n* \"[[Break the Bank (song)|Break the Bank]]\" \u2013 Schoolboy Q\n\n====2015====\n\n* \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2016====\n\n* \"[[That Part]]\" \u2013 Schoolboy Q, [[Kanye West]]\n* \u201c[[John Muir]]\u201d \u2014 Schoolboy Q\n\n====2017====\n\n* \"[[Element (song)|Element]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Feel (Kendrick Lamar song)|Feel]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[God (Kendrick Lamar song)|God]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Love (Kendrick Lamar song)|Love]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Zacari]]\n* \"[[Loyalty (Kendrick Lamar song)|Loyalty]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Rihanna]]\n* \"[[Lust (Kendrick Lamar song)|Lust]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[XXX (Kendrick Lamar song)|XXX]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Yah (song)|Yah]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n\n====2018====\n\n* \"[[All the Stars]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[SZA (singer)|SZA]]\n* \"[[Big Shot (Kendrick Lamar song)|Big Shot]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Travis Scott]]\n* \"[[Black Panther (Kendrick Lamar song)|Black Panther]]\" - Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[Bloody Waters (song)|Bloody Waters]]\" \u2013 [[Ab-Soul]], [[Anderson .Paak]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]\n* \"[[I Am (Jorja Smith song)|I Am]]\" \u2013 [[Jorja Smith]], Kendrick Lamar\n* \"[[King's Dead]]\" \u2013 [[Jay Rock]], Kendrick Lamar, [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]\n* \"[[Opps (song)|Opps]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[Vince Staples]], Yugen Blakrok\n* \"[[Paramedic!]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[SOB x RBE]], [[Zacari]]\n* \"[[Seasons (Mozzy song)|Seasons]]\" \u2013 [[Mozzy]], [[Sjava]], [[Reason]]\n* \"[[The Ways (song)|The Ways]]\" \u2013 Kendrick Lamar, [[Khalid]], [[Swae Lee]]\n* \"[[X (Schoolboy Q, 2 Chainz and Saudi song)|X]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, Schoolboy Q, [[2 Chainz]], [[Saudi (musician)|Saudi]]\n\n====2019====\n\n*\"[[The Lion King: The Gift|Nile]]\" - Kendrick Lamar, [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n*\"[[Lover (album)|London Boy]]\" \u2013 [[Taylor Swift]]\n\n===Albums===\n\n*''[[Section.80]]'' \u2013 Kendrick Lamar (2011)\n*''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther]]'' \u2013 Kendrick Lamar (2018)\n*''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'' \u2013 [[Taylor Swift]] (2019)\n*''[[The Lion King: The Gift]]'' - [[Beyonc\u00e9]] (2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===[[Academy Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Pictures (Original Song) \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Golden Globe Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Pictures (Original Song) \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]]===\n* Won: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] \u2013 \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Good Kid, M.A.A.D City]]'' (2013)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[To Pimp a Butterfly]]'' (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[Alright (Kendrick Lamar song)|Alright]]\" (2015)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]'' (2017)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] \u2013 ''[[Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther]]'' (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]] \u2013 \"[[King's Dead]]\" (2018)\n* Nomination: [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for Visual Media]] \u2013 \"[[All the Stars]]\" (2018)\n\n===[[Guild of Music Supervisors Awards]]===\n* Nomination: Best Achievement in Music Written for Motion Picture